<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="144581ac-9529-5e22-9bb8-0b448bdec529" activityNameId="0cf44080-c762-4eee-9a08-e926c2c3f3d1" parentActivityId="57eeef5f-a09d-52b2-8007-c4ba891126a5" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">potato production</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Solanum tuberosum L</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">This activity starts with soil cultivation after the harvest of the previous crop.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">This dataset includes cultivation of the field prior to planting, field treatments, planting, applications of nutrients and pesticides, and harvest (including grading). It ends with graded potato at the farm gate, prior to hauling and storage.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the production of 1 kg of potato (fresh matter) in the US state of Colorado at farm, with a harvested moisture content of 79.2%. This dataset includes cultivation of the field prior to planting, field treatments, planting, applications of nutrients and pesticides, fumigant, regulator and desiccant, and harvest (including grading).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The average yield of potatoes grown in Colorado for the 2010-2021 seasons was 44,565 kg/ha (wet mass) (USDA NASS (2021)). The dataset reflects the average potato produced in Colorado from 2010 to 2021, inclusive, as that period allows for at least one value from USDA statistics for most parameters and generally three or more.  Potato is a no tillage crop (0% no till, 0% reduced till, 100% conventional tillage) and grown in multiyear rotation, commonly 4-year rotation with other crops. This dataset reflects practices consistent with that.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Area, productivity, use of mineral fertilisers and other agrochemicals, and irrigation inputs are based on farmer data reported to the U.S. Department of Agriculture. This dataset does not consider the use of manure during the production process, although recent studies suggest that the use of manure (green and animal) should be studied and considered, as it could benefit the cultivation of this crop and interest appears to be rising. Lime use is based on soil pH and guidance from agricultural extension offices for potatoes. Field operations and equipment types and fuel use are based on materials provided to growers by the agricultural extension office(s), including farm budgets, and on survey information agricultural extension office(s) collect from growers, in conjunction with row spacing data from USDA Drainage (tile or ditch) is installed on 18.7% based on state-level agricultural survey data from USDA. Irrigation is included based on share of crop irrigated (30.7% over the time period, USDA NASS (2018c)). Chemigation is included in this and is not treated as an additional operation.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Total cropland land use, for all crops, in Colorado decreased by 9% between 1997 and 2017 (NRCS 2020). USDA NASS does not report cropped areas for potatoes prior to 2010. The crop LCI tool allocates land use change to all crops and activities that grew in the last 20 years in the US, and only to them, according to their respective area increase; crops for which planted area decreased are not attributed LUC impacts or credits. Thus, the amount of Land use change, annual crop is zero for Potato grown in Colorado. The total cropland change 1997 to 2017 was -8.6% for all crops in Colorado (NRCS 2020).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Soil characteristics, including pH, are based on the distribution of soil pH sampling results reported in the 2020 Soil Test Summary (Bruulsema and Jones 2021). The share of acidic soils is likely overestimated as more frequent testing is to be expected on soils having needed lime and thus low pH soils are likely to be more represented amongst the collected samples. No anti-erosion practices are assumed in the dataset; instead, the erosion soil loss reported in the U.S. Natural Resources Conservation Service's Natural Resource Inventory is used.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">References</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">USDA NASS (2021) POTATO - PRODUCTION - 2000-2021. US Department of Agriculture (USDA) National Agricultural Statistics Service. https://quickstats.nass.usda.gov (direct query: https://quickstats.nass.usda.gov/results/88567F9F-D7F3-3107-BC9E-BC1236B3DB44)</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">USDA NASS (2018c) 2018 Irrigation and Water Management Survey (2017 Census of Agriculture). US Department of Agriculture (USDA). https://www.nass.usda.gov/Publications/AgCensus/2017/Online_Resources/Farm_and_Ranch_Irrigation_Survey/index.php</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">NRCS (2020) Land Cover/use of non-Federal rural land, by State and year, in the 2017 National Resources Inventory. USDA, Natural Resources Conservation Service. http://www.nrcs.usda.gov/Internet/NRCS_RCA/reports/nri_crop_nat.html, https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/wps/portal/nrcs/rca/national/technical/nra/rca/text/#NRI%20Cropland</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">Bruulsema and Jones 2021. Soil Test Summary 2020. Foundation for Agronomic Research and Plant Nutrition Canada present this 2020 summary of soil test levels in North America. Foundation for Agronomic Research, Plant Nutrition Canada. https://soiltest.tfi.org/about/about_soil_test_summaryaccessed August 30, 2021</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="70f60468-408c-443d-8737-73b65b804f9a">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">0113:Growing of vegetables and melons, roots and tubers</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="a150972e-6242-4692-9e48-0a7e72b5c7f0">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">US-CO</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Production of potato in Colorado (US-CO).</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset reflects current practice for potato in Colorado as of 2021.</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2010-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The valid period covers 2014-01-01 through 2021-12-31 based on primary data sources. The production volumes, areas and applications are covered by data throughout the time period (annual for production and area, alternate years for applications). Due to disruption in 2020, some USDA data was reported for 2021 instead. Because the specific pesticides used show time-dependent trends, the most recent 3 years of data are used to avoid underweighting the most dominant pesticides currently used and to avoid skewing impacts based on compounds no longer in use. Field operations are based on current enterprise crop budgets and change little year to year.  Data for manure applications were only available for time periods prior to the valid period but represent the best available option.</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
