        <unitName xml:lang="en">ha</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">1.28E-4 ha/kg fertilising, by injection (5.704 pass(es) per year). 
The dataset has an effective number of passes for application of mineral fertilisers of 0.00: 5.50 N applications on 94.7% of cropped area, 2.57 P applications on 92.7% of cropped area, 1.60 K applications on 74.0% of cropped area, and 4.13 S applications on 93.0% of cropped area (USDA NASS 2021c, data available for 2016 only). The necessary passes used to apply broadcast N are sufficient to supply the necessary PKS so additional passes beyond that for N application are not required. Applications of N are split between anhydrous ammonia and other NPK fertilsers because they are generally applied differently, with different equipment. Anhydrous ammonia application (knifing/injection) is calculated as market share of N that is anhydrous ammonia * total N applications. Other N application is then: total USDA N applications less applications of anhydrous ammonia. The market share of N that is anhydrous ammonia is calculated from fertiliser market group shares crossed with meeting NPKS nutrient demand (here, 80.34%). Thus, the dataset includes 4.18 anhydrous ammonia applications via injection (4.42 * 94.7% of crop area with applied N) and -4.18 other fertiliser applications via broadcast. Detailed guidance for Colorado potato production is not available. Operations are drawn a multi-state comparison (Patterson, 2015) and the budgets on which it is based, and from a Klamath basin budget (Wilson, et al., 2015).
 Field operations are as identified in crop- and rotation-specific enterprise crop budgets supplied by the regional agricultural extension office (state specific unless otherwise noted) and matched to equipment type in the budget or crop guidance, along with pest management documentation (Hills, et al., 2018, 2020; Hirnyck &amp; Downey, 2006) and summary of practices for commercial production in the US (Belyea, 2010). Field operations are as identified in crop- and rotation-specific enterprise crop budgets supplied by the regional agricultural extension office (state specific unless otherwise noted) and matched to equipment type in the budget or crop guidance, along with pest management documentation (Hills, et al., 2018, 2020; Hirnyck &amp; Downey, 2006) and summary of practices for commercial production in the US (Belyea, 2010).  
Sources:
Patterson, Paul (2015) 2014 Cost of Potato Production Study for Colorado, Idaho, Washington and Wisconsin. University of Idaho College of Agricultural and Life Sciences. 
Wilson, Robert et al (2015) Sample Costs to Produce Potatoes. University of California Cooperative Extension. https://coststudyfiles.ucdavis.edu/uploads/cs_public/4e/f5/4ef54da3-114e-4952-a66a-049765b9a747/15potatofreshmktklamathfinaldraftdec10.pdf
Hills, Karen, et al (2020) Improving Soil Health in Pacific Northwest Potato Production: a Review. American Journal of Potato Research. https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s12230-019-09742-7
Hirnyck, Ronda &amp; Downey, Lisa (2006) Pest Management Strategic Plan for Pacific Northwest Potato Production - REVISION. 
Hills, Karen, et al (2018) Safeguarding Potato Cropping Systems in the Pacific Northwest Through Improved Soil Health. Washington State University. 
Belyea S. et al (2010) Commercial Potato Production in North America. The Potato Association of America. 
Galinato, Suzette (2019) 2019 Cost Estimates of Producing Fresh and Processing Potatoes in Washington. Washington State University. 
USDA NASS (2021c) POTATO - APPLICATIONS, MEASURED IN LB / ACRE / YEAR, AVG (fertilizer and pesticides, amount, number of applications) - 2000-2021. US Department of Agriculture (USDA) National Agricultural Statistics Service. https://quickstats.nass.usda.gov (direct query: https://quickstats.nass.usda.gov/results/910944A6-DEB0-3216-B6B4-F5BA47F1D217)</comment>
