        <name xml:lang="en">limestone, crushed, washed</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">Application of limestone to raise soil pH, 93.45 kg/ha (2.1E-3 kg/kg Potato), calculated as the (mass of lime applied to treated acres (2 t/treated ha)) * fraction of crop area treated with lime (9.45%, from soil pH data from ) / (5  years between applications, based on Laboski C.A.M. and Peters JB  2012). 
 Where other information is not available, the years between applications has been estimated as equivalent to or greater than the recommended re-test time.
Sources: 
Bruulsema T and Jones J D (2021) Soil Test Summary 2020. Foundation for Agronomic Research and Plant Nutrition Canada present this 2020 summary of soil test levels in North America. Foundation for Agronomic Research, Plant Nutrition Canada. https://soiltest.tfi.org/about/about_soil_test_summaryaccessed August 30, 2021; Laboski C.A.M. and Peters JB  (2012) Nutrient application guidelines for field, vegetable, and fruit crops in Wisconsin (A2809). UW Extension. https://walworth.extension.wisc.edu/files/2018/11/Nutrient-Application-Guidelines-for-Field-Vegetable-Fruit-Crops-in-WI-A2809.pdf; Shaver T M (2014) Nutrient Management for Agronomic Crops in Nebraska (rev Dec 2014). The University of Nebraska Institute of Agriculture and Natural Resources. https://extensionpublications.unl.edu/assets/pdf/ec155.pdfaccessed August 30, 2021; Bly A and Gelderman R (2019) Chapter: 25 Liming South Dakota Soils . SDSU Extension . https://extension.sdstate.edu/sites/default/files/2019-09/S-0003-25-Corn.pdf; Mallarino A P, Pagani A, Sawyer J E (2011) Corn and soybean response to soil pH level and liming. Paper presented at the 2011 Integrated Crop Management Conference. Iowa State University.Cooperative Extension Service, Iowa State University of Science and Technology. https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/128983337.pdfaccessed November 17, 2021</comment>
