      <elementaryExchange id="321e52eb-f46d-5866-af31-87afab3660ab" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" casNumber="014302-87-5" amount="-3.54572714374885E-07" elementaryExchangeId="ed2d49f8-110d-4db4-9488-f61c349e6117" formula="Hg+2">
        <name xml:lang="en">Mercury II</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">Emissions of heavy metals to soil are estimated based on the SALCA-heavy metal model (Freiermuth 2006) following the procedure in the ecoinvent agricultural LCI tool (Faist Emmenegger, Délerce-Mauris and Porté 2018 Models Integrated in Ecoinvent LCI Calculation Tool for Crop Production). The balance of heavy metal emissions to soils includes the net change from erosion, leaching, crop removal and fertilizer, manure, lime, planting and deposition.  The crop system carries a share of heavy metals emissions based on the ratio of cropping additions to total additions (additions to crop system divided by additions to crop system plus depostion from air and present in soils) Sources for heavy metals contents include: Heavy-metal contents of plant material, maize (mg/kg dry matter, from Freiermuth 2006). ; Leaching of heavy metals to surface water (Wolfensberger &amp; Dinkel 1997), where drainage is installed ; Deposition of heavy metals to soils, mg per ha per year (Freiermuth 2006). ; Deposition of heavy metals to soils, mg per ha per year (Freiermuth 2006). ; Average heavy metal contents in crop soils, mg per kg soil, based on data for Switzerland (from Keller &amp; Desaules, 2001). state and regional erosion rates are from US NRC National Resources Inventory, 2017. and Drainage on all cropland acres state-wide, including tile drainage (1.7%,) and ditch drainage (4.3%). USDA (2018) 2017 Census of Agriculture, Volume 1, Chapter 2: State Level Data - Table 41.  Land Use Practices:  2017 and 2012 (live table: https://www.nass.usda.gov/Quick_Stats/CDQT/chapter/2/table/41/state/US). US Department of Agriculture (USDA). https://www.nass.usda.gov/Publications/AgCensus/2017/Full_Report/Volume_1,_Chapter_2_US_State_Level/st99_2_0041_0041.pdf. Fertilizer, manure and pesticide application rates are based on USDA NASS data.</comment>
        <uncertainty>
          <normal meanValue="-3.54572714374885E-07" variance="0.04" varianceWithPedigreeUncertainty="0.04"/>
          <pedigreeMatrix reliability="2" completeness="3" temporalCorrelation="3" geographicalCorrelation="1" furtherTechnologyCorrelation="1"/>
        </uncertainty>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Mercury (+2)</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Mercury</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Mercury ion</synonym>
