    <modellingAndValidation>
      <representativeness systemModelId="290c1f85-4cc4-4fa1-b0c8-2cb7f4276dce">
        <systemModelName xml:lang="en">Allocation, cut-off by classification</systemModelName>
        <samplingProcedure xml:lang="en">Data is obtained from state, county and national statistics, agricultural extension offices, and published literature. Data for production, yields, applications of NPKS fertilisers, applications of pesticides, row width, and irrigation (if any) was obtained from the US Dept of Agriculture's National Agricultural Statistics Service and in most cases provides high-quality data spanning the dataset time period. Field operations and energy use are from enterprise crop budgets provided by local agricultural extensions offices and their farmer survey data. Literature data is used where USDA and agricultural extension guidance and data are not available.</samplingProcedure>
        <extrapolations xml:lang="en">Mineral fertiliser applications are crop and location (state and sub-state levels) specific for nutrient applied, based on survey data compiled by the USDA National Agricultural Statistics Service. Specific fertilisers are extrapolated from mineral fertiliser applications to  potato in Colorado and market consumption in the US (IFA 2020).  Organic fertiliser types are extrapolated from animal manure use data for  potato in Colorado (state-level) based on data collected by the USDA Economic Research Service for 2010, 2005 and 2000 and current materials on livestock levels. Rotations are based on published analysis and classification of Cropland Data Layer GIS data for 2012-2018 and other sources (Socolar et al 2021). Corn in a non-repetitive rotation with anything (&gt;4% of land surveyed) else is treated as corn-corn as the most conservative option. The rotation pattern is assumed to steady throughout the period, consistent with number of years classified. Data about tillage practices are from crop-specific GIS data for corn encompassing the dataset years (OpTIS 2020).  Soil characteristics, including pH and clay content, are extrapolated from survey year 2017 (Iowa soil survey, ISPAIDver 8.1.1 2019) and taken as valid for the full time period.  data reported 2020 (pH, SOM) and 1995 (clay, slope, approximated with US average farmland slope and clay content), Drainage tile data from 2012 (reported to USDA for the 2012 agricultural census) is extrapolated as valid from that date through the rest of the time period of the dataset and the distribution of drainage is treated as homogenous for all field crops. Machine usage is modelled with Iowa/midwestern US diesel consumption and field operations set out by the regional agricultural extension office and crop budgets (Lazarus 2020, ISU 2015-2021).  Machine sizes (power) are approximate but based on common, recent surveys and equipment analyses (Lazarus 2020).  Transports are modelled with standard distances.  Emissions are calculated with standard methods according to ecoinvent documentation (Nemecek and Schnetzer, 2011. '01 crop production-direct field emissions natural resources' v1.2, August 2011, available at ) and the World Food LCA Database guidelines and the ecoinvent agricultural LCI tool.</extrapolations>
      </representativeness>
      <review reviewedMajorRelease="3" reviewedMinorRelease="0" reviewedMajorRevision="0" reviewedMinorRevision="25" reviewerId="45c856f2-52e0-4ef3-b8df-770d70319286" reviewerName="Iasonas Ioannou" reviewerEmail="ioannou@ecoinvent.org" reviewDate="2023-10-16">
        <otherDetails xml:lang="en"/>
      </review>
      <review reviewedMajorRelease="3" reviewedMinorRelease="4" reviewedMajorRevision="1" reviewedMinorRevision="52" reviewerId="c4597934-ecac-422c-b431-382e85fdcb83" reviewerName="[System]" reviewerEmail="support@ecoinvent.org" reviewDate="2023-10-16">
